  <!-- PROBLEM / SOLUTION -->
  <section>
    <div class="seclabel"><span class="num">03</span><span>Why it exists</span><span class="ln"></span></div>
    <h2>The problem it solves</h2>
    <p class="lead">Hand-managing several environments breaks down fast. Each failure mode here has a deliberate fix.</p>
    <div class="ps">
      <div class="pscol bad">
        <div class="hd">⨯ Manual multi-env pain</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="ic">!</span><span><b>State chaos</b> — local state files can't be shared and corrupt when two people apply at once.</span></li>
          <li><span class="ic">!</span><span><b>Secrets in git</b> — SSH keys and credentials accidentally committed.</span></li>
          <li><span class="ic">!</span><span><b>Manual server setup</b> — SSH-ing into each box by hand, inconsistently.</span></li>
          <li><span class="ic">!</span><span><b>Repeated code</b> — the same resource blocks copy-pasted per environment.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="pscol good">
        <div class="hd">✓ How this resolves it</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="ic">→</span><span><b>S3 remote backend</b> for central, durable, encrypted state.</span></li>
          <li><span class="ic">→</span><span><b>DynamoDB locking</b> blocks simultaneous applies.</span></li>
          <li><span class="ic">→</span><span><b>Secrets Manager + IAM</b> — key fetched at runtime, never in git.</span></li>
          <li><span class="ic">→</span><span><b>Reusable modules + Ansible roles</b> configure every server identically.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHY TOOLS -->
  <section>
    <div class="seclabel"><span class="num">04</span><span>Stack</span><span class="ln"></span></div>
    <h2>Why each tool</h2>
    <p class="lead">Every choice maps to a specific responsibility in the pipeline.</p>
    <div class="tbl">
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-terraform"/></svg></span>Terraform</div><div class="desc">Declarative, repeatable, version-controlled provisioning — infrastructure as code.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-terraform"/></svg></span>Workspaces</div><div class="desc">Run the same code for many environments, each with isolated state.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-terraform"/></svg></span>Modules</div><div class="desc">DRY, reusable building blocks for EC2, S3, and DynamoDB.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-s3"/></svg></span>S3 backend</div><div class="desc">Central, durable, encrypted state — works for teams, survives a lost laptop.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-dynamo"/></svg></span>DynamoDB lock</div><div class="desc">Prevents two applies from corrupting state simultaneously.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-secrets"/></svg></span>Secrets Manager</div><div class="desc">Stores the SSH private key securely; supports rotation and IAM-scoped access.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-iam"/></svg></span>IAM</div><div class="desc">Terraform and Ansible authenticate via identity — no static keys in code.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-ansible"/></svg></span>Ansible</div><div class="desc">Agentless configuration management — configure or update every server in one run.</div></div>
      <div class="trow"><div class="tool"><span class="lg"><svg><use href="#i-ansible"/></svg></span>Ansible roles</div><div class="desc">Idiomatic structure: tasks, handlers, defaults, and Jinja2 templates.</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RUN STEPS -->
  <section id="run">
    <div class="seclabel"><span class="num">05</span><span>Run it</span><span class="ln"></span></div>
    <h2>Step by step</h2>
    <p class="lead">From bootstrapping the backend to a live landing page served by Ansible.</p>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step">
        <div class="node">1</div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Bootstrap the remote backend (once)</h4>
          <div class="code"><span class="c"># creates the S3 state bucket + DynamoDB lock table</span><br>cd remote-backends<br>terraform init<br>terraform apply        <span class="c"># type: yes</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="node">2</div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Initialize the main project</h4>
          <div class="code">terraform init        <span class="c"># configures S3 backend + providers</span><br>terraform validate</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="node">3</div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Provision <span class="mono" style="color:var(--green)">dev</span></h4>
          <div class="code">terraform workspace new <span class="g">dev</span><br>terraform plan        <span class="c"># 2 EC2, 1 S3, 1 DynamoDB</span><br>terraform apply<br>terraform output</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="node">4</div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Provision <span class="mono" style="color:var(--ans)">prod</span> — same code, different size</h4>
          <div class="code">terraform workspace new <span class="y">prod</span><br>terraform apply        <span class="c"># 4 EC2, 2 S3, 2 DynamoDB</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="node">5</div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Configure servers with Ansible</h4>
          <div class="code">cd ansible-for-devops<br>./generate_inventory.sh   <span class="c"># pulls SSH key from Secrets Manager</span><br>ansible all -m ping       <span class="c"># expect "pong"</span><br>ansible-playbook site.yml <span class="c"># deploy to ALL servers</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="node">6</div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Verify &amp; tear down</h4>
          <div class="code">curl http://&lt;ec2_public_ip&gt;          <span class="c"># see the landing page</span><br>terraform workspace select dev &amp;&amp; terraform destroy</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECRETS -->
  <section id="secrets">
    <div class="seclabel"><span class="num">06</span><span>Security</span><span class="ln"></span></div>
    <h2>How secrets are handled</h2>
    <p class="lead">No keys ever touch the repo. Identity over static credentials, encryption at rest throughout.</p>
    <div class="secrets">
      <div class="panel-card">
        <ul>
          <li><span class="k">gen</span><span>Terraform generates the SSH keypair in code via <span class="mono">tls_private_key</span> — no key files in git.</span></li>
          <li><span class="k">split</span><span>The <b>public</b> key lands on EC2 instances; the <b>private</b> key goes to Secrets Manager.</span></li>
          <li><span class="k">fetch</span><span><span class="mono">generate_inventory.sh</span> pulls the private key at runtime through the AWS CLI, authenticated by your IAM identity.</span></li>
          <li><span class="k">ignore</span><span>The fetched <span class="mono">key.pem</span> is gitignored; Ansible uses it to connect.</span></li>
          <li><span class="k">rest</span><span>Terraform state is encrypted at rest in S3, since it can hold sensitive values.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="principle">
        <div class="pl">Principle</div>
        No secrets in git. Identity-based auth (IAM) over static keys. Encryption at rest — for state, EBS, and S3.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

